Microbial transformation is a biological synthesis process that uses enzymes inside microorganism as biocatalysts. The principal advantages are the environmental safety, mild conditions, and characteristic regio- and stereoselectivities of these biocatalytic processes (

). Thus, this technique permits access to remote positions on molecules and offers a useful alternative to chemical approaches (

).

Excessive and persistent production of cytokines and chemokines are involved in the pathogenesis of infections, allergies, and immune related diseases, such as autoimmune diseases, coronary artery disease, obesity, cancers, and neurodegenerative diseases (

; 

; 

; 

). Cytokines, a class of small cell-signaling proteins, are key modulators of inflammation participating in acute and chronic inflammation (

; 

; 

; 

). Interleukin (IL)-1, tumor necrosis factor (TNF), interferon (IFN)-γ, IL-12, IL-18 and granulocyte-macrophage colony stimulating factor (GM-CSF) are pro-inflammatory cytokines that promote inflammation (

). Chemokines, structurally related chemotactic cytokines, are a specific subclass of cytokines. Chemokines are categorized into four groups: 
C
– 
C
chemokines (monocyte chemoattractant protein (MCP-1), monocyte inflammatory protein (MIP)-1α, MIP-1β, and RANTES), C-X-C chemokines (IL-8 also called growth related oncogene or GRO/KC), 
C
chemokines (lymphotactin), and CX 
3
C
chemokines (

; 

; 

). They are produced during infections, or as a response to inflammatory stimuli, and facilitate immune response by targeting cells of the innate and adaptive immune system (

). Therefore, cytokines and chemokines play a pivotal role in the development, homeostasis, activation, differentiation, regulation, and functions of innate and adaptive immunity (

). Glucocorticoids (GCs), such as dexamethasone, have been known to suppress a plethora of pro-inflammatory genes encoding cytokines, chemokines, cell adhesion molecules, and other mediators, thereby interfering with the inflammatory response (

, 

; 

; 

). GCs have been used as therapeutic treatment in a wide range of autoimmune and inflammatory diseases (

; 

). However, long-term systemic treatment of GCs remain as the cause of unsolved problems, such as the GC resistance or undesired side effects (

; 

). Inhibition of cytokines release can be an alternative therapeutic strategy for alleviating a variety of disorders (

). Thus, agents that modulate cytokine-mediated inflammatory pathways may be considered as an effective therapeutic strategy for preventing inflammatory reactions and diseases (

; 

).

A
great number of naturally occurring 
ent
-kaurane diterpenoids have been isolated from many plant families (

). They have also attracted interest because of their structures and wide range of biological activities (

; 

). According to the literature, tetracyclic diterpenoids possess rigid ring systems, and they have received special attention as substrates for microbial transformation to produce sizable amounts of new compounds otherwise difficult or impossible to synthesize by chemical methods (

; 

). Thus, the aim of this study was the microbial transformation of 
2
to obtain diverse compounds and characterize their new biological activities. Because tetracyclic diterpenoids possess steroid-like skeletons (

) and they are capable of inhibiting proinflammatory cytokines (

; Hueso-Falc´on et al., 2011; 

), the effects of all isolates on LPS-induced cytokine production by THP-1 cells were examined, with dexamethasone used as a positive control. Herein, we describe the production, isolation, and structural characterization of isolates as well as their effects on cytokine production. In addition, interactions of biotransformation products with the active site of the glucocorticoid receptor (GR) were also analyzed through molecular docking.

During the acid hydrolysis of stevioside, 15-ene steviol ( 2 ) was isolated as a minor product by means of silica gel column chromatography. The structure of 2 was characterized by 1D and 2D NMR, HRESIMS, and by comparison with the literature (
). Screening-scale studies were performed with 20 microbial cultures to determine their abilities to transform 2 . Among the different strains screened,
A. niger Tiegh. (Aspergillaceae)
BCRC 32720,
C. bainieri Thaxter var. echinulate (Cunninghamellaceae)
ATCC 9244, and
M. isabellina Oudemans
, teleomorph ( Mortierellaceae ) ATCC 38063 were found to reproducibly convert 2 into several compounds. Preparative-scale bioconversion of 2 with
A. niger
afforded compounds 3–6 . Preparative-scale bioconversion of 2 with
C. bainieri
afforded compounds 6–10 , while with
M. isabellina
produced 4 , 9 , 11 , and 12 ( Fig. 1 ). Among these isolates, ent -13, 16β- dihydroxy-kauran-19-oic acid ( 3 ), ent -13-hydroxy-kaur-16--en-19-oic acid ( 5 ; steviol), ent -13,15β- dihydroxy-kaur-16-en-19-oic acid ( 10 ) and ent -13,17-dihydroxy-kaur-15-en-19-oic acid ( 12 ) have been described previously (
;
;
), while ent -7α,13-dihydroxy-kaur-15-en-19-oic acid ( 6 ) and ent -14β- hydroxy-16-oxo-beyeran-19-oic acid ( 8 ) were reported as their methyl esters, respectively (
;
). Compound 4 was obtained as white crystalline needles with IR absorption at 1272 ( C –O– C ) and 1731 ( C ––O) cm 1 . HRESIMS data of 4 showed a protonated molecular ion at m/z 335.2229 [M +H] + (calcd for C 20 H 31 O 4 , 335.2222). This implied that the molecular formula of 4 was C 20 H 30 O 4 . The 13 C NMR spectrum displayed resonances for 20 carbons, while the DEPT spectrum showed the same carbon multiplicity as 2 . However, comparison of the 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra of 4 and 2 revealed that alkene C –H resonance was absent from 4 , and new resonances at δH 4.51 and δC 75.3 appeared ( Table 1 ; Figs. S1 and S 2 , Supplementary data). Inspection of the HSQC and HMBC spectra revealed that a new proton resonance at δH 4.51 showed connectivities with carbon resonances at δ 43.5 ( C- 8), 84.8 ( C- 13), and 85.2 ( C- 16). CH 3 -17 ( δH 1.60) showed connectivities with δC 57.4 ( C- 15), 84.8 ( C- 13), and 85.2 ( C- 16) ( Fig. 2 ; Figs. S3 S 6 , Supplementary data). In the 1 H– 1 H COSY spectrum, δH 4.51 showed cross-peaks with the methylene group (H-12: δH 2.39, d, J = 10.5 Hz; δH 2.47, m) (Figs. S9 and S10, Supplementary data). Thus, an oxygen bridge between C- 11 and C- 16 was confirmed. The α- orientation of H-11 was established by NOE correlation of δ 4.51 with CH 3 -20 (δ 1.20), H-9β (δ 1.62–1.64), H-1 (δ 1.74–1.80), and H-12 (δ 2.47) ( Fig. 3 ; Figs. S7 and S8, Supplementary data). Moreover, an X-ray crystallographic experiment was used to confirm the structure of 4 ( Fig. 4 ). Thus, 4 was characterized as ent -13-hydroxy-11α,16α- epoxy-kauran-19-oic acid.

Compound 7 was obtained as white cubic crystals. Its HRESIMS indicated a protonated molecular ion at m/z 373.2007 [M +Na] + (calcd for C 20 H 30 O 5 Na, 373.1991) and m/z 349.2026 [M H] (calcd for C 20 H 29 O 5 , 349.2015), suggesting a molecular formula of C 20 H 30 O 5 . The IR spectrum suggested the presence of two carbonyl absorption bands at 1707 and 1735 cm 1 . The 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra displayed one carboxylic carbonyl, one carbonyl group, and seven methylene, four methine, three methyl, and four quaternary carbons (Figs. S11 and S12, Supplementary data). Comparison of the 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra of 7 and 2 revealed that the double bond was absent from 7 and was replaced by a carbonyl group at δ 221.4 ( Table 1 ). An NOE effect was observed between H-15α (δ 2.66) and CH 3 -20 (δ 1.11) (Fig. S18, Supplementary data), suggesting that 7 might possess an ent -beyerane skeleton as does isosteviol ( 1 ) (
). The DEPT and HSQC spectra, compared to those of 1 (
;
), displayed new resonances at δH 4.65 ( δC 71.4) and 4.24 ( δC 84.7), suggesting that 7 was a dihydroxylated product of 1 ( Table 1 ; Figs. S12 S14, Supplementary data). In the HMBC spectrum ( Fig. 2 ; Figs. S15 and S16, Supplementary data), δH 4.65 exhibited cross-peaks with resonances at δC 44.8 ( C- 15), 47.7 ( C- 5), and 49.9 ( C- 9). Thus, hydroxylation had occurred at C- 7. In addition, the second new proton resonance at δ 4.24 showed correlations with resonances at δC 36.3 ( C- 12), 49.9 ( C- 9), and 44.8 ( C- 15), indicating the presence of one OH group at C- 14. In the NOESY spectrum, 7-OH was assigned a β- orientation due to the presence of cross-peaks of H-7 with H-6 (δ 2.42), H-15 (δ 2.47), and H-6 (δ 2.54–2.56). 14α- OH was established from cross-peaks of H-14 with CH 3 -17 (δ 1.38), H-12 (δ 1.47–1.53), and H-9β (δ 1.97) in the NOESY spectrum ( Fig. 3 ; Figs. S17 and S18, Supplementary data). Furthermore, the structure of 7 was confirmed by a single-crystal X-ray crystallographic analysis ( Fig. 4 ). Thus, 7 was characterized as ent -7α, 14β- dihydroxy-16-oxo-beyeran-19-oic acid.

In order to explore binding conformations of dexamethasone with compounds 1–12 , molecular docking was performed with the docking program, CDOCKER algorithm, in Discovery Studio. CDOCKER energy represents interactions of ligand-protein complexes, and a lower interaction energy indicates higher stability. Dexamethasone, as a positive control, had the lowest interaction energy (60.00 kcal⋅mol 1 ). Among the tested compounds, 11 and 12 had lower interaction energies (49.59 and 50.54 kcal⋅mol 1 , respectively), and 10 had the highest interaction energy. Results of CDOCKER energy are tabulated in Table S2 (Supplementary data). Dexamethasone was reported to have higher affinity and greater bioavailability than natural hormones, such as cortisol (
). Its hydrogen bonds and alkyl interactions with key residues in the binding pocket of GR were studied, such as hydrogen bonds of Asn564, Arg611, Gln642, and Thr739 (
). Based on CDOCKER interaction energies, compounds 2 and 10–12 showed differences in their interaction energies according to the molecular docking. Compound 10 was identified as having three hydrogen bonds, but exhibited no interaction with key residues of GR except for an alkyl interaction, while compounds 11 and 12 had more than one key residual interaction bound to the GR similar to what dexamethasone had. Although no compounds showed stronger and more stable interactions with the GR than dexamethasone, the docking results clearly showed their potential and ranking in ability to activate the GR. This result provides preliminary information of 15-ene steviol ( 2 )-derived compounds bound to the GR and initial cascade signaling. Binding modes of dexamethasone, 2 , and 10–12 with the GR are depicted in Fig. 6.

